arch:property.oc:show_val: Opening elevation: 901.36 m (in the north section) and 901.63 (in the south section).

Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.

Locus 21 doorway in Locus 6, connecting the ‘colonnaded corridor’ to the ‘bench room.’ The doorway is constructed with Locus 6, which is constructed of dry-laid hewn and dressed sandstone ashlars. Both sides of the doorway are doorjams, with the longer section to the west, suggesting that the doors would have opened from the ‘colonnaded corridor’ into the ‘bench room.’ There is no clear threshold intact, and there is a step up of approximately 49 cm from the ‘colonnaded corridor’ into the ‘bench room.’ The north section of the doorway is seven courses high and two rows thick; the south section of the doorway is nine courses high and two rows thick. Phased with Locus 6, this locus has been assigned to Stage 3, a long period of additions to the main construction of the Bath Complex.
Additions to the Complex, including the small reservoir, the bathroom and the anteroom.
Doorway between the ‘bench room’ and the colonnaded corridor
